11 (C) for construction; or
12 (2) require a landlord to pay for one (1) or more essential
13 services provided to a rental unit if the landlord has not
14 agreed to do so under the rental agreement.
15 SECTION 3. IC 32-31-8-6.5 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
16 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
17 1, 2026]: Sec. 6.5. (a) This section applies to an action that is filed
18 under section 6 of this chapter after June 30, 2026.
19 (b) During the pendency of an action to which this section
20 applies, if the tenant continues to occupy the rental unit upon
21 which the action is based, the court may issue a provisional order
22 that requires the tenant to make regular rental payments otherwise
23 due to the landlord under the rental agreement to:
24 (1) the clerk of the court, who shall hold the payments in trust
25 for the parties; or
26 (2) an attorney trust account;
27 as directed by the court. The funds held by the clerk or in an
28 attorney trust account under this subsection may not be disbursed
29 unless the court issues an order for their disbursement.
30 (c) Subject to subsection (e), if the tenant is the prevailing party
31 in the action under section 6 of this chapter, the tenant is entitled
32 to a refund of payments made under an order issued by the court
33 under subsection (b). The amount of the refund:
34 (1) shall be determined by the court after taking into
35 consideration:
36 (A) the estimated cost of any repairs or other action
37 necessary to remedy the condition that was the basis of the
38 tenant's action under section 6 of this chapter;
39 (B) any expenses incurred by the tenant in undertaking any
40 repairs or other action necessary to remedy the condition
41 that was the basis of the tenant's action under section 6 of
42 this chapter;
2026 IN 127—LS 6497/DI 129

5
1 (C) any efforts undertaken by the landlord before or after
2 the filing of the tenant's action under section 6 of this
3 chapter to remedy the condition that was the basis of the
4 tenant's action under section 6 of this chapter; and
5 (D) any other factors that justice may require; and
6 (2) shall be disbursed to the tenant upon order of the court.
7 (d) Subject to subsection (e), if the tenant is not the prevailing
8 party in the action under section 6 of this chapter, the tenant is not
9 entitled to a refund of any rental payments made under an order
10 issued by the court under subsection (b), and any amounts held in
11 trust by the clerk of the court or in an attorney trust account shall,
12 upon order of the court, be disbursed to the landlord and credited
13 against the amount of the regular rental payments due to the
14 landlord under the rental agreement during the pendency of the
15 action.
16 (e) The court may reduce the amount of:
17 (1) a refund to be disbursed to a tenant in an order under
18 subsection (c), if the court determines that the tenant
19 contributed in any way to the necessity of repairs or other
20 action needed to remedy the condition that was the basis of
21 the tenant's action under section 6 of this chapter; or
22 (2) any amounts to be disbursed to a landlord in an order
23 under subsection (d), if the court determines that the
24 landlord's failure to comply with one (1) or more of the
25 requirements of this chapter contributed in any way to the
26 necessity of repairs or other action needed to remedy the
27 condition that was the basis of the tenant's action under
28 section 6 of this chapter;
29 as justice may require.
30 SECTION 4. IC 32-31-9-8, AS ADDED BY P.L.22-2007,
31 SECTION 2, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
32 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 8. (a) A landlord may not terminate a lease, refuse
33 to renew a lease, refuse to enter into a lease, or retaliate against a tenant
34 solely because:
35 (1) a tenant;
36 (2) an applicant; or
37 (3) an individual who is a member of the tenant's or applicant's
38 household;
39 is a protected individual.
40 (b) A landlord may not refuse to enter into a lease with an applicant
41 or retaliate against a tenant solely because:
42 (1) the tenant;
2026 IN 127—LS 6497/DI 129

6
1 (2) the applicant; or
2 (3) an individual who is a member of the tenant's or applicant's
3 household;
4 has terminated a rental agreement as a protected individual under
5 section 12 of this chapter.
6 (c) Except as otherwise provided in subsection (b), evidence that
7 a tenant engaged in a protected activity not more than six (6)
8 months before the landlord's alleged retaliatory conduct creates a
9 rebuttable presumption that the purpose of the landlord's conduct
10 was retaliation.
11 (d) A presumption does not arise under subsection (c) if the
12 tenant engaged in a protected activity after the landlord gave the
13 tenant notice of the landlord's intent to:
14 (1) increase the rent or fees;
15 (2) decrease services, increase the tenant's obligations, impose
16 different rules on, or selectively enforce the landlord's rules
17 against, the tenant or immediate family member, or otherwise
18 materially alter the terms of the lease;
19 (3) bring an action for possession on a ground other than
20 nonpayment of rent;
21 (4) refuse to renew a tenancy for a fixed term under a lease
22 containing a renewal option that is exercisable by the tenant
23 without negotiation with the landlord, for any period after the
24 lease would otherwise terminate; or
25 (5) terminate a periodic tenancy.
26 (e) A landlord may rebut a presumption under subsection (c) by
27 a preponderance of evidence showing that the landlord:
28 (1) had sufficient justification for engaging in the conduct that
29 created the presumption; and
30 (2) would have engaged in the conduct in the same manner
31 and at the same time whether or not the tenant engaged in a
32 protected activity.
33 SECTION 5. IC 36-1-20-6, AS ADDED BY P.L.193-2014,
34 SECTION 9, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
35 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 6. (a) This chapter does not prevent a political
36 subdivision from imposing and collecting a penalty for an act or
37 omission that is a nuisance or violation of the political subdivision's
38 enforceable ordinances or codes, subject to subsection (b).
39 (b) A penalty permitted under subsection (a) may not be imposed
40 until after:
41 (1) reasonable notice of the nuisance or violation has been given
42 to the owner or the owner's designee;
2026 IN 127—LS 6497/DI 129

7
1 (2) passage of a reasonable time, which must be stated in the
2 notice, for the nuisance or violation to be cured; and
3 (3) failure of the nuisance or violation to be cured within the time
4 stated in the notice.
5 (c) An owner or the owner's designee must pay all penalties
6 assessed by the political subdivision for violation of an obligation
7 under IC 32-31-8-5 with regard to a rental premises. All penalties
8 must be paid and all repairs required by the political subdivision
9 must be made before delivering the rental premises to a tenant.
